<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Characteristic Species</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Coleogyne</i> <i>ramosissima</i> is dominant or co-dominant in the shrub canopy with <i>Artemisia</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Atriplex</i> <i>confertifolia</i>, <i>Ephedra</i> spp., <i>Ericameria</i> <i>teretifolia</i>, <i>Eriogonum</i> <i>fasciculatum</i>, <i>Grayia</i> <i>spinosa</i>, <i>Krascheninnikovia</i> <i>lanata</i>, <i>Larrea</i> <i>tridentata</i>, <i>Menodora</i> <i>spinescens</i>, <i>Picrothamnus</i> <i>desertorum</i>, <i>Purshia</i> <i>stansburiana</i>, <i>Salazaria</i> <i>mexicana</i>, <i>Thamnosma</i> <i>montana</i> and <i>Yucca</i> <i>schidigera</i>. Emergent trees may be present at low cover, including <i>Juniperus</i> <i>californica</i>, <i>Juniperus</i> <i>osteosperma</i>, <i>Pinus</i> <i>monophylla</i> or <i>Yucca</i> <i>brevifolia</i>. </div>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Vegetation Layers</h4>
	<div class="text">  Shrubs < 2 m; canopy is open to continuous. Herbaceous layer is sparse to open with cryptogrammic crusts. </div>
</div>

        
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Membership Rules</h4>
	<ul class="text">
		
		<li><i>Coleogyne ramosissima</i> ≥ 2% absolute cover in the shrub canopy; <i>Ephedra nevadensis</i> and/or <i>Krameria grayi</i> may be two times the cover of <i>C. ramosissima;</i> the cover of <i>Ambrosia  salsola, Salazaria mexicana, Ericameria</i> spp., or <i>Eriogonum fasciculatum</i> may exceed that of <i>C. ramosissima</i> on disturbed sites (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
		
	</ul>
</div>

        
	
<div class="allianceSection">
	 <h4 class="header">Habitats</h4>
	<div class="text"> Alluvial fans bordering intermountain basins, slopes, upper bajadas, rocky highlands. Thin, sandy soils with abundant exposed rock from mixed alluvium and colluvium, often with a shallow caliche layer, moderate alkalinity and a low tolerance of salinity.  </div>
</div>

        
