<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Coleogyne ramosissima </i>is an aromatic, manybranched shrub with diffuse, shallow roots. Plants are drought deciduous. Small mammals disperse and cache seeds. A scarcity of seedlings indicates that reproduction occurs infrequently, with seed and seedling mortality caused by seed predation, herbivore browsing, and limited soil moisture in the summer. Seed germination requires a period of cold stratification; successful seedling establishment follows heavy, early spring rains (Anderson 2001c). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Coleogyne ramosissima </i>has a long lifespan. Stands are generally simple and monotypic, sometimes with closely spaced shrubs (Webb et al. 1987). Typical stands have shallow soils with caliche layers and welldeveloped cryptogamic crusts between shrubs (West 1988). Stands occur abundantly on old geologic soils but are lacking on young basalt flows, and their cover and density increase with the age of the soils (Webb et al. 1988, 1987). Stands are on the least disturbed geomorphic surfaces in an area; they persist longer than do other plant assemblages on these surfaces (Tueller et al. 1991, Webb et al.1987). <i>C. ramosissima </i>can invade grasslands following overgrazing (Wells 1961). Low soil moisture or cold air drainage set the lower elevation limit, and cold air temperatures set the upper limit of the type (Lei and Walker 1994, 1995). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
