<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Fire Characteristics</h4>
	<div class="text">Fire spreads quickly and easily in closely spaced stands. Stands with an abundant cover of non-native annual grasses are most fire prone. The species does not sprout and is slow to invade sites once burned. The return of shrub dominance may require hundreds of years, and frequent, large fires have eliminated <i>Coleogyne ramosissima </i>in some areas (Anderson 2001c, Webb and Esque pers. comm. 2001). <i>Bromus rubens </i>and <i>B. tectorum </i>act as principal fuels for fires, although following years of high rainfall, <i>Schismus </i>spp. may also carry fire. Succession after fire includes a phase where <i>Stipa speciosa </i>or <i>Pleuraphis rigida </i>dominates for several years before <i>C. ramossisma </i>establishes in the Great Basin and Mojave Desert (M. Brooks, pers. comm. 2004).</div>
	<table class="zebraStripe">
		
		<tr>
