    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Mojave Desert</b> (322Aa, Ad, Af-h, Aj, Al, An, Ap). Stands are common above 1000 m, especially on alluvium underlain by pediments where stands mix with those of the <i>Artemisia tridentata, Atriplex confertifolia, Ephedra nevadensis, Juniperus californica, Juniperus osteosperma, Pinus monophylla,</i> and <i>Yucca brevifolia</i> alliances. Stands recovering from fire and grazing have <i>Gutierrezia microcephala</i> or <i>Salazaria mexicana.</i> Stands cover over 35,500 ha in the eastern and northern subsections (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Mono</b> (341Dh-j). Easily apparent stands occur in upper Owens Valley, on adjacent slopes west of U.S. 395 from Rovana to Bishop, and on the lower slopes of the White Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Er). Stands occur on the eastern escarpment of the range from the Paiute Mountains north to the Buttermilk Country west of Bishop.</li>
        
            <li><b>Southeastern Great Basin</b> (341Fb-f). Stands in the Argus, Coso, Grapevine, Last Chance, and Panamint mountains are adjacent to those of the <i>Artemisia tridentata, Grayia spinosa, Larrea tridentata-Ambrosia dumosa, Menodora spinescens,</i> and <i>Yucca brevifolia</i> alliances (Thomas et al. 2004).</li>
        
            <li><b>Southern California Mountains and Valleys</b> (M262Bi, Bp). Desert slopes from the northern San Bernardino Mountains as far south as Anza-Borrego Desert State Park and adjacent lands have intermittent stands among those of the <i>Juniperus californica, Pinus monophylla,</i> and <i>Yucca schidigera</i> alliances (Spolsky 1979, Keeler-Wolf et al. 1998b).</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Fires in stands with non-native annual grasses, especially with <i>Bromus rubens </i>and <i>B. tectorum, </i>are a significant threat to this alliance. The prospects of maintaining old-growth stands are low unless we identify and manage them as weed-free areas. Isolated, extralimital, relictual stands (Stebbins and Major 1965) are of special interest. </div>
</div>

    

    

